EPISODE_NARRATIVE:
A low pressure system moved across Lake Superior on October 30 and eventually reached Quebec on November 2. A combination of cold air and northwest winds across Lake Superior produced the first significant lake effect snow event of the season. While there was only light snow on October 30 and 31, snowfall rates accelerated around 8 pm on October 31 and continued through 10 am on November 2. 

Heavy snow was isolated to a few locations in Alger, Gogebic, and Houghton counties. In Alger county, Trenary received 11 inches and Shingleton 8 inches; in Gogebic county, Ironwood had 8 inches; in Houghton county, Alston had 11 inches and Hancock picked up 7 inches. A widespread area of 4 to 6 inches of snow covered the remainder of these counties.

A 41 yr. old man drowned when his pickup was blown into a slough. The man was driving along highway 200 near Hurdsfield when he came to a low spot on the highway with bodies of water on either side of the highway. Strong north winds up to 45 mph blew water across the road, which made the road icy. When the man hit the icy spot, his truck was blown into 15 feet of water on the south side of the road. The victim drowned after crawling out of the window of his truck before it completely submerged.

Locally heavy bands of lake effect snow developed across northwest portions of Chippewa county during the early morning hours of the
1st and continued through the morning of the 2nd. Northwest portions of the county...in the vicinity of Whitefish Point and Paradise...received 8 to 10 inches of snow. Accumulations across
the rest of the county ranged from 2 to 5 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weather disturbance moving in from the northwest brought a localized area of 4 to 7 inches of snow to Teller county, north of and into Woodland Park during the early morning hours.

An early surge of arctic air produced lake effect snow squalls off Lake Ontario. Localized amounts of six to nine inches were reported in Jefferson and Oswego counties with ten to sixteen inches reported in Lewis county. In addition, the heavy snow produced frequent whiteout conditions -- blamed for several automobile accidents.

A Great Slat Lake enhanced snow-band" produced heavy snow in the western Salt Lake valley as well.  The Alta ski resort received the most snowfall with 20 inches. A storm system that developed over northcentral Nebraska moved northeast into northwestern Minnesota. Although at first the storm appeared to be warm enough to only produce rain, once snow began to fall on the morning of the 5th, dynamic cooling lead to an all snow event across southcentral and east central north dakota. Luckily, no wind accompanied the storm system and there were no major interruptions in day to day activities. Snowfall totals include 5 inches at Carrington and 6 inches at Bismarck.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE:
A prolonged lake effect snow event across the north half of Upper Michigan was set up by the combination of several weather systems. The event started on November 9 with a closed upper air (500 mb) low over Lake Superior combined with northwest winds between Arctic high pressure in Alberta and a surface low in southern Quebec with an east-west oriented trough across Lake Superior. Heavy snow began  around midnight on Nov 9 in the Ironwood area and spread east to the Keweenaw Peninsula during the daylight hours on the 9th. Meanwhile, another band of heavy snow was established over Munising in central Alger county during the day on the 9th. 

The upper low slowly lifted north and opened into a trough by 7 am on the 10th. The surface trough meanwhile moved south of Upper Michigan. This produced a wind shift from northwest to north during the early morning hours of the 10th that shifted the heavy snows over Munising to western Alger county and eastern Marquette counties. 

When the Arctic high moved southeast to Minnesota on the 12th, the winds shifted back to northwest shifting the lake effect snow to Alger and Luce Counties. Whereas the snow slowly diminished in intensity as the high reached Upper Michigan, it did not stop completely until winds shifted to the southwest the morning of the 14th.

Snow totals included 

Goebic County                   Ontonagon County
Bessemer.......40 inches        Bergland........37 inches
Wakefield......39 inches        Rockland........20 inches 
Ironwood.......30 inches        Bruce Crossing..18 inches

Houghton County                 Baraga County
Chassell.......34 inches        Herman..........25 inches
Pelkie.........24 inches        Three Lakes.....14 inches
Calumet........21 inches        Watton..........12 inches
Houghton.......14 inches 

Marquette County                Alger County
Skandia........27 inches        Wetmore........38 inches
Marquette......13 inches        Shingleton.....35 inches
                                Au Train.......35 inches
Luce County                     Chatam.........33 inches
Newberry.......17 inches        Trenary........25 inches
                                Munising.......20 inches

A cold north-northwest flow of air over the relatively warm waters of Lake Superior resulted in snow squalls across northwest Vilas county.  The snow squalls continued off and on for approximately 60 hours, depositing 16 inches of snow in Manitowish Waters, 20 inches in Winchester and over 2 feet in Presque Isle.  The snow was much lighter farther to the south, but 6 to 8 inches still accumulated in parts of northern Oneida county.

county ranged from 20 to 40 inches.

Heavy lake effect snow occurred over a seven day period.  Total storm accumulations ranged from 6 inches in Elyria (Lorain County) to 69 inches in Chardon (Geauga County).  Other significant storm totals were 50 inches in Shaker Heights (Cuyahoga County), 48 inches in Jefferson (Ashtabula County), 28 inches at Kirtland (Lake County), and 15 inches in Mesopotamia (Trumbull County).  The storm wreaked havoc on power and telephone lines.  Cleveland Electric Illuminating estimated 185,000 customers were without power, some for several days.  Dozens of emergency shelters were opened for people who were without electricity.  In Wickliffe and Willoughby (Lake County), motels and hotels that still had power, were sold out.  Schools throughout northeast Ohio were closed.  Cleveland Hopkins Airport (Cuyahoga County) was closed on two occasions, each due to a commercial airplane skidding off the runway.  Cables were downed on mass transit trains and fallen trees blocked the tracks as well as a number of roads.  Thousands of trees fell or were damaged during the course of the storm.  The ground was already saturated at the beginning of the storm causing shallow rooted trees to topple.  Some trees still had their leaves and the extra weight of the snow on them caused many limbs to fall; an estimated 80 percent of city trees in Shaker Heights (Cuyahoga County) suffered damage.  Most cities used 15 percent of their snow removal budgets and the National Guard was called to help clear snow from roads and the roofs of buildings.  Hundreds of homes, garages, carports, barns and commercial buildings had roofs that collapsed or were severely damaged.  A plastics manufacturing plant in Mentor (Lake County) had a major roof collapse, but no one was on the third shift.  The roof of the Faith Baptist Church (Perry Township, Lake County) collapsed, but no one was in the building.  Also, in Lake County, the roofs of three large storage buildings fell in at an 84 Lumber company in Concord Township.  Everyone was evacuated.  In Ashtabula County, the roof of the Methodist Church in Geneva caved in, and in the city of Ashtabula the roofs of a nursery and a warehouse collapsed.  The roof of a 100 year old barn in Hambden Township (Geauga County) caved in, but all the animals were accounted for.  The roof of the Cleveland Children's Museum (Cuyahoga County) collapsed only a short time after it closed.  A house in Garfield Heights (Cuyahoga County) caught on fire from a downed electric line.  The roof collapsed at Card Pak, Inc. in Warrensville Heights (Cuyahoga County) igniting a fire in which three firefighters suffered minor injuries.   The roof of L. Gray Barrell and Drum Company in Cleveland, (Cuyahoga County) collapsed, critically injuring two workers.  Eight Cablevision workers were slightly injured when lightning struck their customer service office in Cleveland (Cuyahoga County) and shocked them through their headphones.  In Conneaut (Ashland County) four women were rescued from their car, in the nick of time, after it became stuck in the snow on the railroad tracks on the Mill Street Conrail crossing.  The car was demolished by a train, but no one was injured.

Heavy lake effect snow accumulated an average of two to three feet over a 7 day period.  Total storm amounts ranged from 21 inches in Conneautville (Crawford County) to 55 inches in Edinboro (Erie County).  The storm downed numerous trees and limbs, some on buildings, some on power and telephone lines and some across roads, closing them to traffic.  Houses, garages, carports, mobile homes, barns and commercial buildings suffered collapsed or severely damaged roofs from the heavy snow.

A brief but heavy snow shower caused a 12 car pile-up on Highway 16 near La Crosse. Multiple-car accidents also occured on Highway 35, 33 and Interstate 90.

Lake effect snow accumulated 12 to 20 inches in the Lake Michigan shoreline counties between Grand Haven and New Buffalo.  Highway crews were able to keep interstates and primary roads open but, overnight on the 10th and 11th, most secondary roads were impassable.  School closings were the norm and numerous business shut down for at least some shifts.  By the afternoon of the 12th traffic had returned to normal while roads remained snow covered and icy for another day.

Low level moisture caught in a strong northwesterly flow was forced up the western face of the Appalachians and resulted in 2-4 inches of snow in the northern mountain counties as well as high elevations of counties bordering Tennessee on the morning of the 9th. The same scenario resulted in an additional 2 inches of snow in the same areas during the early morning hours on the 10th.

Heavy and persistent bands of Lake Effect Snow buried Warren and McKean Counties.  The jackpot was 21 inches at Lottsville.  14 inches fell in Scandia and Spring Creek.  Lesser amounts fell as far east as Montoursville in Lycoming County.

Low level moisture caught in a strong northwesterly flow was forced up the western face of the Appalachians and resulted in 2-4 inches of snow in the northern mountain counties as well as high elevations of counties bordering Tennessee on the morning of the 9th. The same scenario resulted in an additional 2 inches of snow in the same areas during the early morning hours on the 10th.

Lake effect snow extended from Ludington, in Mason County, to Muskegon, and inland through Lake and Newaygo Counties.  Also affected were Kalamazoo and extreme northwest Cass Counties.
Accumulation amounts ranged from 8 to 14 inches with the heaviest reports in western Kalamazoo County.  Main roads were not affected but some wecondary roads were blocked for a 4 to 6 hour period on the 10th.  Some schools were also closed.

Freezing drizzle deposited a half an inch of ice on a 20 mile section of Interstate 90 near Kadoka. Five car accidents resulted.
Cool, but shallow, arctic air was in place.  Areas of rain moved through the area from the southeast, falling as freezing rain at the surface around Anchorage.

The first significant lake effect snow event of the season had its greatest impact on Oneida and Madison counties.  A single band off Lake Ontario dumped 6 to 10 inches of snow on northern sections of Oneida county during the morning and early afternoon of the 11th.  The band then began to drop southward into central Oneida county and dumped anywhere from 8 to 11 inches of snow from about Verona eastward through the Rome and Utica areas.  Eventually, the heavy snow band made it into northern Madison county late on the 11th and early on the 12th.  Cazenovia and Madison received 6 to 8 inches of snow during this time frame, while Oneida township got nearly 14 inches.  The northern suburbs of Syracuse in extreme northern Onondaga county also got locally substantial accumulations.  Cicero picked up about 7 inches.

Arctic air crossing Lake Ontario produced lake effect snow squalls which persisted for nearly four days. Apparently weakening somewhat during the daylight hours, the squalls reintensified overnight. Numerous automobile accidents --some with injuries-- were blamed on the whiteouts and hazardous driving conditions. Various school districts cancelled classes because of the storm. Snowfall totals in Oswego county ranged from 12-25
column40: in Jefferson county from 10-15" and in Lewis county from 20-30"."

Widespread fog developed over north central Montana late in the day Monday, November 11th and persisted for the next several days.  This caused ice to slowly build up on exposed surfaces.  By the 13th, ice 6 to 8 inches thick on power lines was causing widespread power outages, especially in Glacier, Toole, Liberty, and Pondera counties.  On the 14th, strong winds developed.  Many ice covered power poles were blown down, creating more power outages.  The area near Sunburst was hardest hit where 100-150 poles were knocked down.  Estimated damages were between $150,000 and $200,000.

Snow squalls occured across portions of northern Vermont during the evening of Tuesday, November 12, 1996. The hardest hit area was Chittenden County with between 3 and 6 inches reported countywide.

Freezing drizzle coated power lines and roads throughout western South Dakota.  In Perkins county, up to 3 inches of ice was reported on power lines.  Over 300 distribution poles were downed at a cost of over $300,000.  In and around Rapid City, over 40 car accidents were reported, resulting in the hospitalization of four people with serious to critical injuries.

An upper level disturbance moved east northeast from the southern and central Rockies into the central plains as low pressure strengthened over eastern Colorado.  Freezing rain was widespread across the area causing several telephone outages, power outages,  and auto accidents.  Nearly 40,000 Omaha Public Power District (OPPD) customers in west Omaha lost power for a period of time from 11/14/96 during the early evening hours until 11/15/96 during the morning hours.

Winter storm began approximately 4 PM CST on the 14th with freezing drizzle causing numerous accidents across the area.  Freezing drizzle changed to snow on the 15th with amounts ranging from 3 inches at North Platte to as much as 9 inches around O neill.  Fifty power poles were snapped off in the O neill area.  Power outages were common across the area.

An ice storm consisting of several periods of freezing rain caused widespread damage to power lines and poles, and to trees. Power lines snapped, cable wires were ripped down, and tree debris littered and blocked some roads. Thousands lost power, some for 5 days. Travel was curtailed by icy surfaces and there were numerous accidents, although no serious injuries were reported. The ice storm was described as the worst in 40 years in the Worthington area. Many small farm structures were damaged. A 600 foot radio tower in Worthington was toppled. Schools and business were forced to close. Damage continued after the ice storm ended, including some damage occurring when ice melted unequally during later milder weather. The total extent of the damage was expected to be unknown for a long time.

Iowa had been under the dominance of a large Arctic air mass for several days prior to this event.  Temperatures failed to reach the freezing point for many days.  As a result, surfaces were cold and the ground began freezing.  Warm air surged northward aloft over the state driven by a 40 to 50 kt low level jet.  Meanwhile, a large storm system developed to the southwest of Iowa.  Overrunning precipitation began to form in bands during the afternoon of the 14th.  It was in the form of freezing drizzle and ice pellets at first.  Later in the evening and into the morning of the 15th, a steadier period of freezing rain developed with embedded thunderstorms.  Most areas did not receive a great deal of freezing rain, however the roads became covered with ice.  Travel was hazardous with the Iowa D.O.T. recommending no travel in some sections of the state, especially over the north half.  Nearly all the schools in the state were either closed or on two hour delay on the morning of the 15th.  Little damage occurred with the storm other than countless traffic accidents.  The far northwest was the only are reporting significant damage.  In the Estheville area of Emmet County, Emergency Managers reported numerous trees and power lines, as well as a few power poles, downed by the ice loading.  Amounts in that area were in the half to three quarter inch range.  By mid day, the warm air had surged north at the surface bringing temperatures above the freezing point.  Conditions improved rapidly during the late morning and early afternoon.

Most areas did not receive a great deal of freezing rain, however the roads became covered with ice.  Travel was hazardous with the Iowa D.O.T. recommending no travel in some sections of the state, especially over the north half.  Nearly all the schools in the state were either closed or on two hour delay on the morning of the 15th.  Little damage occurred with the storm other than countless traffic accidents.  The far northwest was the only are reporting significant damage.  In the Estheville area of Emmet County, Emergency Managers reported numerous trees and power lines, as well as a few power poles, downed by the ice loading.  Amounts in that area were in the half to three quarter inch range.  By mid day, the warm air had surged north at the surface bringing temperatures above the freezing point.  Conditions improved rapidly during the late morning and early afternoon.

Winter storm began approximately 4 PM CST on the 14th with freezing drizzle causing numerous accidents across the area.  Freezing drizzle changed to snow on the 15th with amounts ranging from 3 inches at North Platte to as much as 9 inches around O neill.  Fifty power poles were snapped off in the O neill area.  Power outages were common across the area.

Freezing drizzle changed to snow on the 15th with amounts ranging from 3 inches at North Platte to as much as 9 inches around O neill.  Fifty power poles were snapped off in the O neill area.  Power outages were common across the area.

An ice storm consisting of several periods of freezing rain caused widespread damage to power lines and poles, and to trees. Power lines snapped, cable wires were ripped down, and tree debris littered and blocked some roads. Thousands lost power, some for 5 days. Travel was curtailed by icy surfaces and there were numerous accidents, although no serious injuries were reported. The ice storm was described as the worst in 40 years in the Worthington area. Many small farm structures were damaged. A 600 foot radio tower in Worthington was toppled. Schools and business were forced to close. Damage continued after the ice storm ended, including some damage occurring when ice melted unequally during later milder weather. The total extent of the damage was expected to be unknown for a long time.

Amounts in that area were in the half to three quarter inch range.  By mid day, the warm air had surged north at the surface bringing temperatures above the freezing point.  Conditions improved rapidly during the late morning and early afternoon.

An ice storm consisting of several periods of freezing rain caused widespread damage and paralyzed travel. Widespread damage occurred to electrical poles and lines, leaving thousands without power for up to four days. Numerous accidents occurred, including many vehicles which slid off the road. One fatality occurred in a semi accident on Interstate 90 near Plankinton on November 14th. Two fatalities occurred 9 miles south of Coleman when a car slid off a gravel road and into a stream, drowning the occupants, also on November 14th. A school bus slid into a ditch near Lennox on November 18th, causing four minor injuries. Several injuries due to falls were reported in the Sioux Falls area. Many surfaces were coated with more than an inch of ice, making gravel roads as slippery as paved roads. Tree damage was widespread with tree debris blocking several roads and siedwalks. Some farm buildings and other small structures were damaged by the weight of ice and snow on roofs. Damage continued past the ending of the ice storm, including some damage when ice melted unevenly during later milder weather. The total extent of the damage was expected to be unknown for a long period.

Two fatalities occurred 9 miles south of Coleman when a car slid off a gravel road and into a stream, drowning the occupants, also on November 14th. A school bus slid into a ditch near Lennox on November 18th, causing four minor injuries. Several injuries due to falls were reported in the Sioux Falls area. Many surfaces were coated with more than an inch of ice, making gravel roads as slippery as paved roads. Tree damage was widespread with tree debris blocking several roads and siedwalks. Some farm buildings and other small structures were damaged by the weight of ice and snow on roofs. Damage continued past the ending of the ice storm, including some damage when ice melted unevenly during later milder weather. The total extent of the damage was expected to be unknown for a long period.

CZ_NAME_STR: GORE AND ELK MOUNTAINS/CENTRAL MOUNTAIN VALLEYS/ASPEN AND VICINITY / NE S EAGLE / PITKIN EXCEPT XNC / X NE MESA / SE GARFIELD (PART) (ZONE)
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm pattern which began on the 14th resulted in a persistent series of snowfall events for western Colorado.  The precipitation quit or changed to rain on the 18th as a warmer air mass spread into the area.  Total snowfall accumulations for the period generally ranged from 1 to 2 feet above the 8000 foot level, with 8 to 12 inches between the 6000 foot level and 8000 foot level.  Heavier amounts were reported, including 35 inches at Steamboat Springs.  Many traffic accidents occurred during the period.  Windy conditions in some areas caused blowing and drifting snow which compounded the travel difficulties.

Schools closed or began late over much of southern Minnesota the morning of the 15th.  1/2 inch thick ice common over the area.  Flights canceled at Minneapolis/St. Paul International Airport due to ice forming on airplanes and runways, however mainly sleet was reported in the Twin Cities.  Much of the ice melted later on the 15th as temperatures warmed above freezing.

A winter storm developed over the Four Corners region, moved into southwest Colorado and brought on average 4 to 6 inches of snow. However, a storm total of 28 inches was reported at Wolf Creek ski area, and 32 1/2 inches at Summittville at 11,500 feet. In addition, gusty southwest winds up to 60 mph over the higher peaks produced widespread blowing and drifting snow and whiteout conditions.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Around a foot of new snow fell in parts of the North Central Mountains, Front Range Foothills and Middle Park. One of the worst ice storms in a few decades affected Vilas, Oneida and northern Lincoln counties.  Trees, power lines and roads were coated with between one-half inch and 2 inches of ice during the event.  The combination of ice accumulation and winds gusting to 30 mph resulted in thousands of downed trees, branches and power lines.  Power outages affected at least 50 towns and 12,000 people.  As many as 120 electrical line crews were called in from all parts of Wisconsin and Upper Michigan to assist in the restoration effort, which was described as the largest in the past 10 years.  despite this massive effort, some customers were without power for over 3 days.  Community shelters were set up to provide food and warmth for those affected by the storm.

A strong area of low pressure brought 6 to 9 inches of snowfall to most of central and to parts of north central South Dakota. Snowfall amounts include, 6 inches at Kennebec, Blunt, and Miller, 7 inches at Murdo, Ft. Pierre, Pierre, and 23N Highmore, 8 inches 2NE Iona and 9NNE Reliance, and 9 inches 12SSW Harrold. Travel was significantly affected, along with a few minor accidents. Also, some sporting events and activities were postponed or canceled.

Ice Storm 96 began on Novemeber 16th with heavy snow falling in Northern Idaho.  The morning of the 17th reports from Bonner County at 8 am included 20 inches new snow at Bonner's Ferry, with 5 inches additional on the 18th and 19 inches new at Naples with 6 new on the 18th. November 18th through the 21st schools were closed in Bonner's Ferry with over three feet of new snow at most of the schools.  Some roads were closed.  Schools were also closed in Couer d'Alene, Sandpoint, in Nezperce and Highland in Lewis County where 14 inches of new snow fell.  St. Maries and neighboring communities were without power beginning on the 18th.  November 19th freezing rain plagued the North coating many power lines and trees with heavy ice.  Clearwater, Idaho and Kootenai Counties were without power due to fallen trees and power lines.  In Kootenai County traffic was slowed everywhere.  Officals were overwhemled with traffic accidents and snow removal.  Three feet of snow also fell at Mullan from the 17th through the 20th, closing I-90 for periods of time as well as many other roadways and Highway 96 at Burma.  
Effects from this strom were felt through the remainder of the month.  By Novemeber 21st, 29 inches of new snow fell at Bonner's Ferry collasping several roofs of homes and buisnesses.  On Novemeber 24th, a barn collasped in Kootenai County killing 7 cows.  Novemeber 26th, Kootenai and Boundary County residents are still without power.   November 27th, narrow roads still blocked in Northern Idaho.  By November 28th, a break in the weather after 10 days with snow, freezing rain, fallen trees, and no power, crews were able to begin power restoration work.  Damage estimates were around 6 million for Northern Idaho.

Schools were also closed in Couer d'Alene, Sandpoint, in Nezperce and Highland in Lewis County where 14 inches of new snow fell.  St. Maries and neighboring communities were without power beginning on the 18th.  November 19th freezing rain plagued the North coating many power lines and trees with heavy ice.  Clearwater, Idaho and Kootenai Counties were without power due to fallen trees and power lines.  In Kootenai County traffic was slowed everywhere.  Officals were overwhemled with traffic accidents and snow removal.  Three feet of snow also fell at Mullan from the 17th through the 20th, closing I-90 for periods of time as well as many other roadways and Highway 96 at Burma.  
Effects from this strom were felt through the remainder of the month.  By Novemeber 21st, 29 inches of new snow fell at Bonner's Ferry collasping several roofs of homes and buisnesses.  On Novemeber 24th, a barn collasped in Kootenai County killing 7 cows.  Novemeber 26th, Kootenai and Boundary County residents are still without power.   November 27th, narrow roads still blocked in Northern Idaho.  By November 28th, a break in the weather after 10 days with snow, freezing rain, fallen trees, and no power, crews were able to begin power restoration work.  Damage estimates were around 6 million for Northern Idaho.

Moist onshore Pacific flow brought heavy early season snow to the North Oregon Cascades. Santiam Pass received 21 inches, the Mount Hood area 7 inches.

One mile west of Libby, MT 11.5 inches of new snow recorded in 24 hours ending at 300 PM 12/17/96. 6.5 inches of new snow recorded at Troy, MT from 145 AM to 645 AM on 12/17/96, with another report from Troy of 7 inches at 800 AM. At 700 AM 12/17/96 Lincoln County Sheriff reported 6 to 8 inches of new snow south of Libby. By 300 PM on 12/18/96, Libby, MT recorded another 11 inches of new snow.
Deborgia, MT in Mineral County reported 9.5 inches new snow by 1100 AM 12/17/96.

Heavy snow, strong winds, and cold temperatures gripped the area during the first blizzard of the season.  Northwest winds gusted from 25 to 45 mph, with the station at Fargo, ND reporting numerous gusts to 42 knots.  8 to 13 inches of snow fell over the entire area, with 13.5 inches total in Fargo and 11 inches in Grand Forks.  Interstate 29 was closed and Interstate 94 was closed from Valley City to Fargo.  Although not included as a storm death, a University of North Dakota student died from exposure in this storm.  Other factors contributed to his death.
